# Analytics reports (HTML + report.css)

Offline reports under `scripts/analytics/` share one design library. **Reports differ by markup only** — not by per-report CSS or class names.

Read the block comment at the top of `scripts/analytics/report.css` before editing styles or templates.

## report.css

- **Only** reusable report-library rules: tokens (`--report-*`), elements (`nav`, `section`, `table`, `button`), and generic patterns (`.card`, `.grid`, `.copy-row`, `.small`, `.sep`).
- **Never** add selectors named after a report or feature (`visit-pulse-*`, `growth-story-*`, etc.).
- Prefer **element selectors** and existing shared classes over new one-off classes.

## HTML templates (`*.html`) and report builders (`*.js`)

- Use **semantic structure** and classes already defined in `report.css` (`nav`, `main`, `section`, `.card`, `.grid`, `.copy-row`, …).
- **Do not** invent template-only or report-specific **CSS class names** for layout or look. If styling is needed, extend the shared library in `report.css` in a generalized way, or use a semantic element (`nav`, not `.report-top-links`).
- **`data-*` attributes** are fine for behavior (delegated clicks, copy payloads) — they are not styling hooks.
- Avoid inline `style=""` in templates except truly dynamic values (e.g. chart swatch colors from data).
- Generated HTML inlines `report.css` via `report-styles.js`; do not add separate per-report stylesheets.

## Examples

```html
<!-- BAD: report-scoped styling class -->
<p class="visit-pulse-day-nav">…</p>

<!-- GOOD: shared library + semantics -->
<nav class="small" aria-label="Report navigation">…</nav>
```

```css
/* BAD */
.visit-pulse-chart { padding: 12px; }

/* GOOD — any report with a chart wrapper can use this */
.chart-wrap { padding: 12px; }
```

## When something is report-specific

Put it in that report’s **HTML content or JS data**, not in `report.css` and not in a report-named class. Reusable UI patterns discovered while building one report belong in `report.css` only after generalizing the name and structure.
